<br>
Other leaders have taken a &quot;Three-strikes&quot; approach (sometimes &quot;Two-strikes&quot;) - meaning you get a warning or two, and then you are gone.<br>
<br>
On dragon raids, the actions of a single person rarely result in mass deaths (well... I'm sure some people remember a case where a certain Paladin caused quite a number of deaths... but we don't talk about that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).  On plane raids, however, a single person doing something as simple as sitting down at the wrong time can result in EVERYONE dying... so it doesn't even take a person <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>actively</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> trying to cause problems, only someone not paying enough attention.  I'd probably be a lot more likely to boot people immediatly on a plane raid... but it really does depend on the leader.<br>
<br>
In general, at least from my experience, people that come to KCoG raids tend to be pretty decent folks.  Sure, you'll get trouble makers from time to time, but ultimately they tend to do themselves more harm than anyone else.  It can get awefully hard to play the game when you get a bad reputation with a large number of guilds... <p>-Kommisar Nils "Can-Head" Hansen -- Guild Officer. Master Smith. Tank.
KCoG Dragon Liason (retired)
